### **Abstract**

ACDC (Active Cat Detection Companion) helps cat owners monitor and care for their pets by tracking food, water, and treats using multiple Arduinos. One Arduino measures food weight, another tracks water level, a third dispenses treats when a specific cat is detected via RFID, and a fourth manages alerts and overall communication. Data is shared wirelessly for easy monitoring. A buzzer and LED notify owners when the cat approaches. Unlike typical feeders using cameras, ACDC uses accurate sensors and RFID detection for personalized, reliable feeding, ensuring no bowl runs empty and every cat receives proper attention.

### **Detailed Project Ideas**

Our idea is to create a useful way to monitor your cats water, food, and treat usage. We want to make sure their water bowl is never empty, their food never low, and keep their treats always stocked. We do this by attaching monitors to their feeding bowls that alert us when their supply is low. This then lets us make sure to refill their containers. Additionally, we plan to include a treat dispenser that will detect when a specific cat is present to give an appropriate amount of treats. The treat dispenser will only be triggered when the cat with a specific collar id is present by using RFID technology to detect and differentiate the cat's ids. 

Arduino 1 will be used as a food monitor. This will be accomplished through a weight scale. If the food weight goes under a certain amount then the monitor will alert the user priming them to fill the food bowl. Arduino 2 will be used as a water monitor. The monitor will be a Solu SL067 water level sensor letting us know when the water level drops below a certain level prompting us to refill the water level. Arduino 3 will be used as a treat dispenser. The treat dispenser will only be triggered when the cat with a specific collar id is present by using RFID technology to detect and differentiate the cat's ids. The way it would dispense would be through a motor which rotates and dispenses a treat as if it were a gumball machine. Arduino 4 will be used as an alert system keeping track of all the other monitors. Arduino 4 will also be used as a control for the treat dispenser where the user can press a button and it will allow the treat dispenser to go off. 

The communication between all Arduino will be done through wifi mainly but for the cat treat dispenser we will also be using bluetooth. A RFID (Radio Frequency IDentification) receiver, like a RC522, will send out a RF signal to power passive tags attached to the cat's collar and receive the tags backscattered response. The response will be decoded by the RC522 module and sent to the Arduino through the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI). The Arduino themself will use wifi to share information to the controller which is the 4th Arduino explained earlier. 

1. We will use a weight scale input to track the amount of food in a bowl.  
2. We will use a water level sensor input to track the amount of water.  
3. We will use a proximity sensor input to sense when a cat is near the dispenser.  
4. We will use an LED output to indicate that the cat is near the dispenser.  
5. We will also use a sound buzzer to indicate that the cat is near the dispenser.  
6. We will use a pushbutton or a detected RF signal input to trigger a treat to be dispensed.  
7. We will use a servo motor output to spin the treat dispenser handle.  
8. We will use an RFID tag attached to the cat's collar to transmit data when the cat is close to the dispenser and an antenna/reader to receive data. This data will include information such as the cat's id.

The project already exists since an automatic cat feeder exists already, but what sets us apart is the sensors and treat feature we are adding. We are specifically using arduinos sensors to check the weight of the cat food being dispensed and adding a water level sensor. Most cat dispensers use a camera to measure this. In a way our dispenser would be more accurate than a camera sensor. Most of us have a fuzzy four-legged friend so we will be able to test this live and make adjustments as needed.

**Arduino ID:** Master/Hub  
**Description:** This Arduino will act as an access point. The other Arduinos will be clients that connect to this “master” hub to report their data. An LCD is also connected to report the data.

**Global Variables:**

| DECLARE VARIABLE food\_level AS FLOAT DECLARE VARIABLE water\_level AS STRING // e.g., "OK", "LOW" DECLARE VARIABLE cat\_id\_present AS STRING // Stores the ID of the cat at the dispenser DECLARE VARIABLE is\_cat\_nearby AS BOOLEAN  |

**Setup Function:**

Start a server to listen for client Arduinos	CREATE a server that listens on a specific port	PRINT "ACDC Hub is online. Waiting for connections..."              // 3\. Initialize the LCD Screen       INITIALIZE LCD display (      CLEAR the LCD screen       SET LCD cursor to first line       LCD PRINT "ACDC System Boot"       SET LCD cursor to second line LCD        PRINT "Waiting for data..."	 	// 4\. Set initial default values for system variables	SET food\_level TO 0.0       SET water\_level TO "UNKNOWN"       SET cat\_id\_present TO "NONE"       SET is\_cat\_nearby TO FALSE END FUNCTION |

**Arduino ID:** Food Weight  
**Description:** This Arduino reads the current weight of the food and sends it to the master Arduino. It begins by connecting to the Arduino networks once and then proceeds to read new data which is sent to the master’s server.	

**Global Variables:**

| // WiFi and Server details for the Master HubDECLARE CONSTANT WIFI\_SSID AS STRING \= "ACDC\_Cat\_System"DECLARE CONSTANT WIFI\_PASSWORD AS STRING \= "your\_password\_here"DECLARE CONSTANT HUB\_IP\_ADDRESS AS STRING \= "192.168.4.1"DECLARE CONSTANT HUB\_PORT AS INTEGER \= 80// Pins for the load cell amplifier (e.g., HX711 module)DECLARE CONSTANT LOADCELL\_DOUT\_PIN AS INTEGER \= 3DECLARE CONSTANT LOADCELL\_SCK\_PIN AS INTEGER \= 2// This value is found by calibrating the scale with a known weightDECLARE CONSTANT CALIBRATION\_FACTOR AS FLOAT \= \-450.5  |
| :---- |

**Setup Function:**

| FUNCTION setup():    // 1\. Initialize the scale    INITIALIZE scale library with LOADCELL\_DOUT\_PIN and LOADCELL\_SCK\_PIN    SET the scale's calibration using CALIBRATION\_FACTOR        // 2\. Tare the scale to zero. Assumes the empty bowl is on the scale at startup.    TARE the scale // Sets the current reading to be "0 grams"    PRINT "Scale is tared. Ready for food."    // 3\. Connect to the Master Hub's WiFi network    INITIALIZE WiFi in client mode    CONNECT to WiFi network using WIFI\_SSID and WIFI\_PASSWORD        WHILE WiFi is not connected:        WAIT for 500 milliseconds        PRINT "Connecting to WiFi..."        PRINT "Successfully connected to ACDC Hub network\!"END FUNCTION |
| :---- |

**Main Loop:**

| FUNCTION loop():    // 1. Read the weight from the scale (e.g., in grams)    DECLARE VARIABLE current\_weight AS FLOAT    SET current\_weight TO the value read from the scale    // Ensure the weight is not a negative number (can happen with cheap sensors)    IF current\_weight \< 0 THEN        SET current\_weight TO 0.0    END IF    // 2. Connect to the Master Hub's server    CREATE a WiFi client    IF the client can connect to HUB\_IP\_ADDRESS on HUB\_PORT THEN        PRINT "Connected to Hub. Sending weight data..."        // 3. Format the data and send it        // The Hub is programmed to understand the "FOOD:" prefix        CREATE VARIABLE message AS STRING \= "FOOD:" \+ current\_weight        SEND message to the Hub server        PRINT "Data sent: " \+ message                // 4. Disconnect from the Hub        DISCONNECT the client    ELSE        PRINT "Hub connection failed."    END IF    // 5. Wait before sending the next update    WAIT for 30 seconds END FUNCTION |
| :---- |

**Arduino ID:** Treat dispenser   
**Description:** This Arduino first detects if a cat is in proximity. If the cat is within a foot of the treat dispenser then it turns the servo motor 180 degrees dropping a treat and then resets.

**Global Variables:**

| // Hardware Pin AssignmentsDECLARE CONSTANT PROXIMITY\_SENSOR\_PIN AS INTEGER \= 7DECLARE CONSTANT SERVO\_MOTOR\_PIN AS INTEGER \= 9// System Behavior SettingsDECLARE CONSTANT TRIGGER\_DISTANCE\_CM AS INTEGER \= 30 // Approx 1 footDECLARE CONSTANT COOLDOWN\_PERIOD\_MS AS LONG \= 300000 // 5 minutes in milliseconds// State Variable// Stores the time (in milliseconds) when the last treat was dispensedDECLARE VARIABLE last\_dispense\_time AS LONG |
| :---- |

**Setup Function:**

| FUNCTION setup():    // 1\. Configure hardware pins    SET pin mode for PROXIMITY\_SENSOR\_PIN to INPUT    INITIALIZE and ATTACH the servo motor to SERVO\_MOTOR\_PIN    // 2\. Set the servo to its default "closed" position    MOVE servo to 0 degrees    // 3\. Initialize the timer    // Set last\_dispense\_time to a large negative value on startup    // This ensures the dispenser is ready to be used immediately.    SET last\_dispense\_time TO \-COOLDOWN\_PERIOD\_MS        PRINT "Treat dispenser is armed and ready."END FUNCTION |
| :---- |

**Main Loop:**

| FUNCTION loop():    // 1\. Get the current system time    DECLARE VARIABLE current\_time AS LONG \= get\_milliseconds\_since\_startup()    // 2\. Check if the cooldown period has passed    IF (current\_time \- last\_dispense\_time) \>= COOLDOWN\_PERIOD\_MS THEN        // If we are NOT on cooldown, check the sensor                // 3\. Read the distance from the proximity sensor        DECLARE VARIABLE distance\_cm AS INTEGER \= read\_distance\_from\_sensor(PROXIMITY\_SENSOR\_PIN)        // 4\. Check if a cat is close enough to trigger the dispenser        IF distance\_cm \< TRIGGER\_DISTANCE\_CM THEN            PRINT "Cat detected\! Dispensing a treat."                        // 5\. Dispense the treat and update the timer            CALL dispense\_treat()            SET last\_dispense\_time TO current\_time            PRINT "Dispenser is now on a 5-minute cooldown."        END IF    END IF        // The loop automatically repeats. If it's on cooldown, the first IF statement    // will be false, and nothing will happen until the 5 minutes are up.        WAIT for a short moment (e.g., 100 milliseconds) to prevent rapid, unnecessary readsEND FUNCTION |
| :---- |

**Helper Function:**

| FUNCTION dispense\_treat():    // Turn 180 degrees to open the dispenser    MOVE servo to 180 degrees    WAIT for 1 second    // Turn back to 0 degrees to close it    MOVE servo to 0 degrees    WAIT for 1 secondEND FUNCTION |
| :---- |
